.el .ds Aq '
.TH compare 1  "compare " 
.SH NAME
compare \- Compare two execution trace JSON files side\-by\-side
.SH SYNOPSIS
\fBcompare\fR [\fB\-o\fR|\fB\-\-output\fR] [\fB\-\-ignore\-path\fR] [\fB\-\-ignore\-field\fR] [\fB\-h\fR|\fB\-\-help\fR] <\fITRACE_A\fR> <\fITRACE_B\fR> 
.SH DESCRIPTION
Compare two execution trace JSON files side\-by\-side
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\fB\-o\fR, \fB\-\-output\fR \fI<OUTPUT>\fR
Output file for the comparison report (default: stdout)
.TP
\fB\-\-ignore\-path\fR \fI<PATH>\fR
Ignore a JSON path during comparison. Repeatable. Paths are slash\-delimited, for example: /storage/fee_pool or /return_value/meta/timestamp
.TP
\fB\-\-ignore\-field\fR \fI<FIELD>\fR
Ignore an object field name anywhere in the trace during comparison. Repeatable. Useful for timestamps, sequence numbers, and similar metadata
.TP
\fB\-h\fR, \fB\-\-help\fR
Print help
.TP
<\fITRACE_A\fR>
Path to the first execution trace JSON file (trace A)
.TP
<\fITRACE_B\fR>
Path to the second execution trace JSON file (trace B)
